# QuantumAtlas server (qatlasd) — generated by `qatlasd config init`
#
# This is a minimal template: only the fields you most likely need to
# touch on a fresh install. The exhaustive reference lives at
# https://github.com/IAI-USTC-Quantum/QuantumAtlas/blob/main/.env.example
# (and in `docs/deployment/server-config.md`).
#
# All fields are commented out — uncomment + fill the ones you need.
# `qatlasd` reads with godotenv "non-override" semantics: any env var
# already in the process environment (systemd `Environment=`, shell
# export, docker `-e`) wins over what this file says.
#
# After editing, restart the server:
#   systemctl restart qatlasd            # system service
#   systemctl --user restart qatlasd     # user service
# Then verify: `curl http://127.0.0.1:4200/api/health | jq`.

# ─── Public URL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Canonical https origin this server is reachable at. Used to mint
# OAuth callback URLs and public-facing links.
# QATLAS_SERVER_URL=https://atlas.example.com

# ─── GitHub OAuth (required for browser login) ───────────────────────
# Create an OAuth app at https://github.com/settings/developers
# (callback: https://<server>/api/oauth2-redirect). Fail-closed:
# if QATLAS_ALLOWED_GITHUB_LOGINS *and* QATLAS_ADMIN_GITHUB_LOGINS
# are both empty, nobody can sign in (deliberately locked default).
# GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=
# GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=
# QATLAS_ALLOWED_GITHUB_LOGINS=your-gh-login,teammate-gh-login
# QATLAS_ADMIN_GITHUB_LOGINS=your-gh-login

# ─── Neo4j (graph features; optional but core) ───────────────────────
# Without these, /api/graph/* endpoints degrade to {available:false}
# and `/api/health` reports neo4j: not_configured. The rest of the
# server (wiki, papers, PAT) keeps working.
# NEO4J_URI=bolt://localhost:7687
# NEO4J_USERNAME=neo4j
# NEO4J_PASSWORD=

# ─── Object storage / S3-compatible backend (RustFS, MinIO, R2, ...) ─
# All six S3 fields must be set together or all left empty. Half-set
# config is a startup fatal (avoids quiet writer/reader skew). When
# unset, qatlasd falls back to a local filesystem store under
# QATLAS_RAW_DIR (~/.local/share/quantum-atlas/raw by default) —
# fine for dev, NOT recommended for prod (no presigned URLs, no
# versioning, no cross-edge sharing).
# QATLAS_S3_ENDPOINT=https://rustfs.example.com
# QATLAS_S3_BUCKET_PDF=qatlas-pdf
# QATLAS_S3_BUCKET_MD=qatlas-md
# QATLAS_S3_BUCKET_IMAGES=qatlas-images
# QATLAS_S3_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# QATLAS_S3_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# Optional public-facing endpoint for presigned URLs (needed when
# server↔storage is mesh-only but clients hit a separate public host):
# QATLAS_S3_PUBLIC_ENDPOINT=https://raw-public.example.com

# ─── System PAT (operator breakglass; optional) ──────────────────────
# Single bearer token loaded from env (never landed in pb_data).
# Useful for: bootstrap, CI / cron, recovery when PocketBase is sick.
# Generate: `openssl rand -base64 32` or `python -c 'import secrets;
# print(secrets.token_urlsafe(32))'`. Must be ≥16 chars or boot fails.
# QATLAS_SYSTEM_PAT=
# QATLAS_SYSTEM_PAT_SCOPES=*

# ─── Bind / storage roots (defaults usually fine) ────────────────────
# QATLAS_HTTP_ADDR=127.0.0.1:4200
# QATLAS_RAW_DIR=    # default: $XDG_DATA_HOME/quantum-atlas/raw
# QATLAS_DATA_DIR=
# QATLAS_PB_DATA_DIR=
# QATLAS_WIKI_DIR=   # default: <this file's parent dir>/../QuantumAtlas-Wiki

# ─── Edge label (multi-edge audit only) ──────────────────────────────
# Folded into S3 client User-Agent so RustFS notify events can tell
# different edges apart at a glance. Cosmetic; do not use for auth.
# QATLAS_EDGE_NAME=us-east
